</table>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Computer_programming" title="Computer programming">computer programming</a>, <b>intentional programming</b> is a collection of concepts which enable software <a href="/wiki/Source_code" title="Source code">source code</a> to reflect the precise information, called <i>intention</i>, which programmers had in mind when conceiving their work. By closely matching the level of <a href="/wiki/Abstraction_(computer_science)" title="Abstraction (computer science)">abstraction</a> at which the programmer was thinking, browsing and maintaining <a href="/wiki/Computer_program" title="Computer program">computer programs</a> becomes easier.</p>
<p>The concept was introduced by long-time <a href="/wiki/Microsoft" title="Microsoft">Microsoft</a> employee <a href="/wiki/Charles_Simonyi" title="Charles Simonyi">Charles Simonyi</a>, who led a team in <a href="/wiki/Microsoft_Research" title="Microsoft Research">Microsoft Research</a> which developed an <a href="/wiki/Integrated_Development_Environment" title="Integrated Development Environment" class="mw-redirect">Integrated Development Environment</a> called <b>IP</b> that demonstrates these concepts. For reasons that are unclear,<sup id="cite_ref-tr1_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tr1-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Microsoft stopped working on intentional programming and ended development of IP in the early 2000s.</p>
<p>An overview of intentional programming is given in Chapter 11 of the book <i>Generative Programming: Methods, Tools, and Applications</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
